<br>
Losing the debate?  What that we don't agree with the fallacious premise that Paladins should have the same or close to the same defensive melee skill as a true specialist?  <br>
<br>
It's not a matter of &quot;winning or losing&quot;, it's a matter of having a different outlook on things.  I happen to feel that in the area of heart surgery, I want a cardiologist over a general practician.  In th area of transmission repairs, I want a certified tranmission technician over a general mechanic, and likewise in every other area I can think of, a specialist should always be preferred over a generalist (read hybrid, one who does it all).<br>
<br>
You on the other hand, seem to think that if the general practitioner has studied medicine, he should be doing heart surgery at a similar rate to the cardiologist, the mechanic in the gas station should be doing the transmission at the same rate as the transmission technician, and so on and so forth.  <br>
<br>
I happen to believe that in the absence of the specialist, a generalist is an acceptable alternative, or when generalist is preferable, such as in regular heart scans, and whatnot, then they're fine, but when you want the best, you call in the big guns.<br>
<br>
I feel the same way about Everquest, the warrior is the defensive melee specialist.  He functions in life solely to fill that one role, and when that one role is needed, he should be the logical choice.  In the absence of him, then a generalist would do a fine job, or when a generalist is needed, such as in hard to mez areas, undead areas, etc.  But when you want the best, the best should ALWAYS be the warrior.<br>
<br>
This is not a matter of &quot;winning or losing&quot; a debate, and anyone who supposes that he's capable of winning a debate about positions, has some serious ego issues, or some logic comprehension issues.<br>
<br>
