<br>
You're right, it sucks.  There are three factors that go into gaining agro for a Warrior.  Total haste, damage ratio, and agroing procs.  And guess what, Warriors have perhaps the hardest time getting all three.<br>
<br>
Haste is pure and simply a PITA.  Warriors are probably the class most desperate for haste just to do their job.  Not to do it more effectively, but just to do it.  How many Rogues/Monks/Rangers level up just fine with minimal haste until they get their epics?  They can perform their group function just fine without it.   Sure, things go faster if they do have it, but its not impossible without it.  How many Paladins/Shadow Knights hold agro just fine without significant haste?  Now put a Warrior in the group without reasonable haste and have the other melee have reasonable haste.  How well does that taunt button work now?   Like crap.  <br>
<br>
So either you get lucky on a drop someplace, and out roll all the other people in your pick up group for it, or you get lucky in a guild group and they award it to you, or your guild gets it for you, or you drop 30-100k on it.  Yikes, that sucks ass doesn't it.  How many classes can you name that will have to drop a minimal of 30k on a piece of gear just to do their basic job description?<br>
<br>
High damage ratio weapons, well they used to be hard to come by.  Now a days they are much easier, on that I think we can all agree.  But ratio alone seems to be mediocre taunt at best, particularly when grouped with Rogues/Monks/Rangers who have weapons of similar calibre and pump out a ton more damage as well.<br>
<br>
Finally, finding a weapon with a high agro proc at a reasonable price is just insane.  Most are a minimum of 10k just to get in the door, and these aren't very good.  There are a few that are reasonable, here and there, but they usually have pretty bad damage ratios.  So you can expect to pay HUGE amounts of plat for decent weapons, and the sky is the limit there.  Or you wait to get very very lucky with your guild someplace.<br>
<br>
And all this just to do something that a Paladin or a Shadow Knight can do with a vendor bought spell.  Seems kind of jacked up doesn't it?<br>
